readme:
Service Usage

This service uses the Enterprise Correspondence Service (ECS) to generate standard correspondence using information from the message. In particular, this service will:
Gather data (if necessary);
Generate correspondence; and
Email the correspondence.
Although the service is synchronous in responding with a correspondence id, the actual sending of the correspondence is asynchronous.

Service Behaviour

This service generates standard correspondence in the following steps:
The consumer calls the service with information that will allow ECS to generate and dispatch the correspondence;
The ESB will validate the message;
If ESB determines the message is erroneous it will send an error message back to the consumer; for example, if the XML is not compliant to the schema;
If ESB determines the message is correctly formed it will call an ECS API;
ECS will validate the template data and, if erroneous, will send an error message back to the consumer;
If ECS determines the message is correct it will send a success status back to ESB
If ECS determines the message is incorrect it will send an error status back to ESB
ESB will return the status to the consumer.
It is important to understand that the job of this service is to deliver the necessary data to ECS for it to generate and dispatch stock correspondence, but not to wait on the generation and dispatch of the correspondence. A success message back to the consumer only indicates that ECS has received the message and will process it at some stage; it does not indicate the success or otherwise of ECSs attempts to generate and dispatch the correspondence.
The service uses SOAP/XML. A consumer of this service receives an Enterprise status message.

Service Variants

None

Service Dependencies

Service Composition

Service Flow

The Service Consumer which invokes the Dispatch Stock Correspondence service on the ESB;
If the consumers message is not well-formed then ESB will send an error to the consumer;
If the consumers message is well-formed according to the ESB then the DispatchStockCorrespondenceRequest message is transformed into the AutogenerateAndDispatchRequest message for ECS;
If ECS have a problem processing the message an error is sent back to the ESB;
If ECS can further process the message a success status is sent back to ESB. The success status indicates that ECS can process the message further and does not indicate that the message has either been generated into correspondence or that the correspondence has been dispatched.
The status is then returned to the consumer. If the consumer receives a success status then they should check later that the correspondence was generated and dispatched.
Outside of this service an event will be returned to the consumer informing them of the actual outcome of the correspondence, e.g. Email dispatched.
Note: The ECS web service XSD will not be one-to-one aligned with the SV322 XSD. Transformation will be required at the ESB level for:
Request message (transform from ESB version to ECS version). Should be limited to changing attribute names. Values to be unchanged.
Response message (transform from ECS version to ESB version). May require transformation on the error codes, but otherwise values to be unchanged.
Please refer to the ESB micro document for transformation details.
Alternate Flow 1 (AF1)
The following alternate service flow depicts the execution path that takes place when the primary provider raises an error.
ESB transforms errors into Enterprise Error Message.
ESB returns response with Enterprise Error payload.
Alternate Flow 2 (AF2)
If the service call was timeout, ESB should return ENTR00007 to the consumer.

Transformation

Service State Management Decisions

No state management.
